          "body": "Jewish tradition counts exactly seventy nations in the Table of Nations, corresponding to the seventy descendants of Jacob who enter Egypt (Exodus 1:5) and to Moses' appointment of seventy elders (Numbers 11:16). Deuteronomy 32:8 (LXX) reads: 'When the Most High gave the nations their inheritance, when He separated the sons of man, He set the boundaries of the peoples according to the number of the sons of Israel.' The seventy nations of Genesis 10 and the seventy Israelites of Exodus 1 stand in deliberate numerical correspondence — the nations and Israel are God's parallel projects, not competing ones. Jesus sends out seventy disciples in Luke 10:1 in an act that echoes the table — a Jubilee mission to all the nations. Revelation 7:9 sees the end of the story: 'a great multitude which no one could count, from every nation and all tribes and peoples and tongues, standing before the throne.' Genesis 10's seventy names are the seed; Revelation 7:9 is the harvest. The Table of Nations is not the record of dispersion — it is the list of invitees to the eschatological feast."
